⁴ It is scarcely possible to identify the places here named, no clue at all being given as to their locality. There is a Peter de Westiby, described in one charter as “serviens Prioris,'’ who occurs some scores of times as a witness to divers documents in the Gysburne Chartulary, and of course Westiby is a local name, but where it was is uncertain. The orthography of the second name is probably as it stands in the text⁷ though the initial might possibly be intended for a D. As to Slethom, the only place so named that I am acquainted with is the Slethollme named at p. 125 of Kirkby's Inquest, and of which the Editor mistakenly writes that it is pro- bably an error for Lealholm. Lealholm was in the Brus fee, and is, more- over, specially dealt with in the documents connected with the partition‚ whereas Sletholm is specified as being in the Mauley see. It was in fact, as is made quite certain by documents in the Gysburne Chartulary, more in the Ugthorpe direction, and I have little doubt that its local site is marked by the farm now called Barnby Sleights.
